      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Use a node with an ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNCamera",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " instance assigned to its ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNNode/camera",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " property to view a scene. The node provides the position and direction of a virtual camera, and the camera object provides rendering parameters such as field of view and focus.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "For debugging lights and shadows, you can also designate a spotlight (an ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNLight",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " object whose ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNLight/type",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " property is ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/lighttype/1523568-spot",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": ") as a point of view. In this case, the light’s ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNLight/spotInnerAngle",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " property determines the field of view, and its ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNLight/zNear",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " and ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.scenekit/documentation/SceneKit/SCNLight/zFar",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " properties determine the near and far extents of the region that is visible onscreen (also known as the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "text": "viewing frustum",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ],
              "type": "emphasis"
            },
            {
              "text": ").",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "In either case, the direction of view is along the negative z-axis of the node’s local coordinate space.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
